      {
         "id": "SECTION_generations",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>How many generations do we have?</h3><p>The answer for this question is linked with the available data. Before we attempt to estimate the number of generations, some factors must be taken into account: <ol><li><b>Life Expectancy Limit:</b> Given the freedom afforded by writing systems, we could set a maximum lifespan allowed by telomeres (<htcite0>).</li> <li><b>Average Generation Span</b>: Across millennia, human cultures and behaviors have evolved, necessitating an understanding of the intervals at which new generations emerge. Drawing from the research of Richard J. Wang <i>et al.</i> , we consider an average generation span of 30,7 ± 4,8 years for men and 23,2 ± 3,0 years for women over the past 250,000 years (<htcite1>).</li> <li><b>Simplifications</b>: Richard J. Wang et al.' work presents an uncertainty in their measurements denoted by '±', this variability is inherent in all measurements and is acknowledged in our simplified demonstration. We will also consider the average generation for men are 31 years while for women are 23 years.</li></p><p>With these considerations in mind, we can proceed to estimate the number of generations since the inception of writing systems approximately 5500 years ago:</p><p><table class=\"mathexample\"> <tr><th>Math steps</th><th>Values</th><th>Dimensional analisis</th></tr> <tr><td>Write the values</td> <td colspan=\"2\">5500 years ÷ 31 years/generation</td></tr>  <tr><td>We isolate numbers from dimensions</td> <td>5500 ÷ 31</td> <td>years ÷ years/generations</td></tr> <tr><td>Perform mathematical operations</td> <td> 177.41935 ≈ 177</td> <td>generations</td></tr><tr><td>Integration of results</td> <td colspan=\"2\"> 177 generations</td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Equation 1</b>: Approximation of the Expected Number of Generations per Individual since the Discovery of Writing Systems.<br />Final rounding occurs due to the representation of generations as integer values.</p><p>According to the research conducted by Richard J. Wang <i>et al.</i>, our species has existed for approximately 250,000 years. Applying this same logic to the timeframe in question, we can estimate the approximate number of generations:</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "66c80cb5-4531-44f7-bbd4-3dd0ac7110e9",
                     "text": "Steenstrup, Troels, et al.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2017",
                        "month": "04",
                        "day": "26"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "dd34414b-8f55-4e5e-877a-c0e111e871be",
                     "text": "Wang, Richard J., et al.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "11",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2017",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2023",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"mathexample\"> <tr><th>Math steps</th><th>Values</th><th>Dimensional analisis</th></tr> <tr><td>Write the values</td> <td colspan=\"2\">250,000 years ÷ 31 years/generation</td></tr>  <tr><td>We isolate numbers from dimensions</td> <td>250.000 ÷ 31</td> <td> years ÷ years/generations</td></tr>  <tr><td>Perform mathematical operations</td> <td> 8064.516129 ≈ 8064</td> <td>generations</td></tr><tr><td>Integration of results</td> <td colspan=\"2\"> 8064 generations</td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Equation 2</b>: pproximation of Expected Generations since Speciation.<br />Final rounding is necessary due to the representation of generations as integer values.</p><p>The analysis reveals that when considering only generations since the advent of writing systems, we tend to underestimate the number of ancestors within our lineage. Consequently, this limitation hampers our understanding of the evolutionary trajectory of our species.</p><p>In this section of History Tracers we focus on specific species within the <i>Homo</i> family. For a deeper exploration of our prehistoric ancestors, readers are encouraged to delve into the works of Charles Darwin (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>), Ian Tattersal & Jeffrey H. Schwartz's paper (<htcite2>), and text available on Britannica encyclopedia website ( <htcite3>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e1339d6e-ab15-42c8-a75b-7a42fa47fffd",
                     "text": "Darwin, Charles, 19--",
                     "page": "Vol. I",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "29"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "57763a8f-035c-490b-8612-8e4c7cd4c10a",
                     "text": "Darwin, Charles, 19--",
                     "page": "Vol. II",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "29"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "874aa098-3b00-4047-9cb7-bf5f9d080691",
                     "text": "Tattersall, Ian, and Jeffrey H. Schwartz.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
