      {
         "id": "SECTION_neanderthal",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Homo neanderthalensis</h3><p>They are commonly known as Neanderthals (<htcite0>), are classified as an archaic human species (<htcite1>). They are also referred to as a subspecies, <i>Homo sapiens neanderthalensis</i> (<htcite2>).</p><p>Despite having a brain size comparable to that of  <i>Homo sapiens</i>, Neanderthals possessed distinct physical characteristics (<htcite3>).</p><p>Occupying various regions across Earth from approximately 200,000 to 30,000 years ago, Neanderthal fossils have been discovered in the Levant, Europe, and Asia (<htcite4> ; <htcite5> ; <htcite6>).</p><p>Interbreeding between <i>Homo neanderthalensis</i> and <i>Homo sapiens</i> (<htcite7> ; <htcite8>), albeit infrequently compared to other primate species (<htcite9>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
