      {
         "id": "SECTION_sapiens",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Homo sapiens</h3><p>When we trace family lineages using surnames, such as the Tavares family, we are engaging in a practice rooted in recent history, as writing systems emerged only a few millennia ago (<htcite0>). However, delving into the history of our species, <i>Homo sapiens</i> (<htcite1>), reveals a much longer and profound journey (<htcite2> ; <htcite3>), prompting questions about our identity: Who are we? What defines <i>Homo sapiens</i>?</p><p>The designation of our species was bestowed by Carolus Linnaeus over a century before the publication of Charles Darwin's seminal work. Linnaeus aimed to delineate Homo sapiens from closely related species (<htcite4>).</p><p>Our understanding of Homo sapiens' characteristics is largely derived from well-defined genetic markers found in mitochondrial DNA and the Y chromosome. Collectively, these genes give rise to distinctive physical traits, including a brain with a volume of 1350 cubic centimeters, a skull with a shortened base, and modifications in bone and muscle structure (<htcite5>).  Additionally, research suggests the possibility of categorizing <i>Homo sapiens</i>, as a subspecies, <i>Homo sapiens sapiens</i> (<htcite6>).</p><p>All families documented in this project belong to the same species, <i>Homo sapiens</i>. However, this may change over millennia as new speciation processes unfold (<htcite7>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "22c3824d-559b-4341-b999-cd0bb39c6246",
                     "text": "Encyclopedia Britannica",
                     "page": "History of writing systems",
