            {
               "text": "<p>The concept of a \"mitochondrial Eve\", metaphorically refers to a common ancestor shared by all individuals mentioned on this site. While this notion is contested by some researchers, such as Francisco J. Ayala who argues against: \"The inference that all humans descend from only one very few women(1) is based on a confusion between gene genealogies and individual genealogies\" (<htcite0>). Conversely, Alan G. Morris <i>et al.</i> support the idea which suggests that this common ancestor lived approximately 200,000 years ago (<htcite1>), citing the work of Doron M. Behar <i>et al.</i> (<htcite2>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c24f6950-c415-42f8-b61b-634a4613d7ff",
                     "text": "Ayala, Francisco J.",
